0","1025–Female":"1025–Afdød","about 1050":"omkring 1050","1125":"1125","1025":"1025","about 1070":"omkring 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","after 1125":"efter 1125","1070":"1070","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"about 1050–after 1125":"circa 1050–na 1125","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1050–Female":"1050–Overleden","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1025–1130":"1025–1130","1025–Female":"1025–Overleden","about 1050":"circa 1050","1125":"1125","1025":"1025","about 1070":"circa 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","after 1125":"na 1125","1070":"1070","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1050–after 1125":"about 1050–after 1125","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1025–1130":"1025–1130","1025–Female":"1025–Deceased","about 1050":"about 1050","1125":"1125","1025":"1025","about 1070":"about 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","after 1125":"after 1125","1070":"1070","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Cornhill on Tweed, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cornhill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name in SE England mainly from Cornhill in London but elsewhere alternatively from Cornhill (Northumb) or one of the many minor places so called. It has often become   Cornell   and has sometimes been confused with   Cornwall  , and   Cornwell  , as in the case of Thomas Cornell, 1722 in   Parish Registers   (Horringer, Suffolk), who is also called Cornwall (1736), Cornwell (1740) and Cornhill (1766).","2  English:  see  Cornall  .","3  English:  see  Cornwall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cornwall","meanings":["English:","habitational name from the county of Cornwall, which is named with the Old English tribal name <i>Cornwealas</i>. This is from <i>Kernow</i> (the term that the Cornish used to refer to themselves, a word of uncertain etymology, perhaps connected with a Celtic element meaning ‘horn, headland’), + Old English <i>wealas</i> ‘strangers, foreigners’, the term used by the Anglo-Saxons for British-speaking people.","variant of   Cornwell  ."]},{"name":"Parish Registers","meanings":["English:  see  Lonsdale  .   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes Tobias Londsdale or Lansdall, 1675–84 in   Parish Registers   (Keighley, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Cornwell","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Cornwell in Oxfordshire, named from Old English <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cron</i>, <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>well(a)</i> ‘spring, stream’.","variant of   Cornwall   or <b>Cornhill</b>; in southeastern England mainly a habitational name from Cornhill in London but elsewhere alternatively from Cornhill (Northumberland) or one of the many minor places so called, often becoming   Cornell  ."]},{"name":"Cornell","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Cornwell  ,   Cornwall  , or of <b>Cornhill</b>, a habitational name from a place in Northumberland named Cornhill, from Old English <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cron</i>, <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’; or from Cornhill in London, a medieval grain exchange, named with Old English <i>corn</i> ‘corn, grain’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’, or from some other place elsewhere similarly named.","English: variant of   Corney  .","English: possibly also a nickname from French <i>corneille</i> ‘rook, crow’, probably denoting a chatterer or someone with dark hair or a dark complexion."]},{"name":"Cornall","meanings":["1  English: the Lancs name is a variant of   Corney  , where  <i>-all</i> and  <i>-ell</i> are hypercorrect pronunciations of  <i>Cornah</i>,  <i>Corner</i>, and  <i>Cornoe</i>, late pronunciations of  <i>Corney</i>.","2  English: the Devon name is a variant of   Cornwall  . Here also probably belongs  <i>Gurnall</i>, as in Joan Gurnall, 1586 in   IGI   (Crediton, Devon), and William Gurnall, 1650 in   IGI   (Lavenham, Suffolk).  Compare  Corney  ."]}]},{"name":"Hubert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."],"variants":[{"name":"Hupprecht","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Huppert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Hugbert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":16,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":36,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":46,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, a